Question 1¶

Write a query to retrieve the artist names along with the total number of tracks each artist has, sorted in descending order of the number of tracks.

SELECT distinct name as ArtistName,
       count(cm_track) as TotalNumberOfTracks
FROM I_cm_track_cm_artist
     LEFT JOIN cm_artist on I_cm_track_cm_artist.cm_artist=cm_artist.id
GROUP BY cm_artist
ORDER BY TotalNumberOfTracks desc

Question 2¶

Write a query to find the artist names along with the total number of tracks each artist has and the release year of their earliest album, sorted by artist name.

SELECT distinct cm_artist.name as ArtistName,
       count(I_cm_track_cm_artist.cm_track) as TotalNumberOfTracks,
       year(min(cm_album.release_date)) as EarliestAlbumReleaseYear
FROM I_cm_track_cm_artist
     LEFT JOIN cm_artist on I_cm_track_cm_artist.cm_artist=cm_artist.id
     LEFT JOIN cm_track on I_cm_track_cm_artist.cm_track=cm_track.id
     LEFT JOIN I_cm_track_cm_album on cm_track.id=I_cm_track_cm_album.cm_track
     LEFT JOIN cm_album on I_cm_track_cm_album.cm_album=cm_album.id
GROUP BY ArtistName
ORDER BY ArtistName

Question 3¶

Implement a query to find the track names that have been associated with multiple artists, along with the names of those artists.

SELECT distinct cm_track.name as TrackName,
       GROUP_CONCAT(cm_artist.name SEPARATOR "*italicized text*, ") as Artists
FROM I_cm_track_cm_artist
     LEFT JOIN cm_track on I_cm_track_cm_artist.cm_track=cm_track.id
     LEFT JOIN cm_artist on I_cm_track_cm_artist.cm_artist=cm_artist.id
GROUP BY cm_track
HAVING count(I_cm_track_cm_artist.cm_artist) > 1
ORDER BY TrackName

Bonus¶

Write a query to find the artist names along with the average follower count and the running total of follower counts for each artist from the cm_artist_cache_history table.

WITH temp AS (SELECT cm_artist.name as ArtistName,
                     cm_artist_cache_history.cm_artist as ArtistID,
                     TRUNCATE(AVG(follower_count), 2) as AverageFollowerCount
              FROM cm_artist_cache_history
                   LEFT JOIN cm_artist on cm_artist_cache_history.cm_artist=cm_artist.id
              GROUP BY ArtistName, ArtistID
              ORDER BY ArtistName, ArtistID
             )
SELECT ArtistName,
       AverageFollowerCount,
       sum(AverageFollowerCount) over (order by ArtistName, ArtistID) as RunningTotal
FROM temp
ORDER BY ArtistName, ArtistID

Data Cleaning¶

In a separate DataFrame: For every distinct CM_ID, find the corresponding SPOTIFY_PLAYS, SPOTIFY_POPULARITY, TIKTOK_TOP_VIDEOS_VIEWS, and AIRPLAY_STREAMS.

  1. Remove any duplicate rows from the dataset.
  2. Filter out rows where the SPOTIFY_POPULARITY is less than 10.
In [4]:
# Create a copy to avoid inadvertent changes to original dataset
dc = Dataset.copy()
# Remove records that don"t have an ID since they won"t be usable in next step
dc = dc.dropna(subset=["CM_ID"])
# Correct CM_ID type to string rather than float since it"s an ID value
dc["CM_ID"] = dc["CM_ID"].astype(int).astype(str)
# Match the metric values to unique CM_ID
dc = dc.groupby(["CM_ID"]).agg(
    {
    "SPOTIFY_PLAYS": "mean",
    "SPOTIFY_POPULARITY": "mean",
    "TIKTOK_TOP_VIDEOS_VIEWS": "mean",
    "AIRPLAY_STREAMS": "mean"
    }
)
# Reset index after group_by()
dc = dc.reset_index()
# Sort data frame by CM_ID (alphabetically since CM_ID is string)
dc = dc.sort_values(by="CM_ID")

# [1.] Remove duplicates (across all columns, including CM_ID)
dc = dc.drop_duplicates() #This should not do anything since there should be no duplicates after applying groupby().

# [2.] Remove rows with SPOTIFY_POPULARITY < 10
dc = dc[dc["SPOTIFY_POPULARITY"] >= 10]

# Display first 5 rows of cleaned DataFrame
dc.head()

Technically, the method employed above relies on the mean being the correct value for SPOTIFY_PLAYS, SPOTIFY_POPULARITY, TIKTOK_TOP_VIDEOS_VIEWS, and AIRPLAY_STREAMS. This will work well for records that have simply been duplicated. If there are records with the same CM_ID and conflicting values, they are still averaged, and this is therefore potentially creating bad/unreliable values, depending on what the contextually appropriate method for handling these conflicts should be (e.g. first value, latest value, weighted average, de-duplicated unweighted average, etc).

Inspection of the dataset suggests that repeated rows differ by UPC and/or spelling of ALBUM_NAME, but the quantitative metrics appear mostly duplicated where values of TRACK_NAME, ARTIST_NAME, and ISRC are the same.

Thus, the data is consolidated in two steps. First, the records are aggregated by TRACK_NAME, ARTIST_NAME, and ISRC, using means for all numeric values. This attempts to find the "true" value for each recording (ISRC is the unique identifier for recordings). Then, these means are summed for the actual numeric values and averaged for the percentage numeric values across TRACK_NAME and ARTIST_NAME. This attempts to approximate the total number of streams/plays and the overall monthly/weekly percentage increases/decreases, grouping together all recordings of each track.

Ideally, context and knowledge of the data collection process/sources should inform deduplication. If album-level information is of interest, the analysis could easily be tweaked to include ALBUM_NAME or another variable in the group_by() criteria.

Transparently, I was kind of confused by the instructions here, so I made a lot of assumptions/educated guesses about what was being asked. With no data dictionary (there was a Notion link? in the pdf, but it was not public/accessible), I was unsure what the variables were exactly.

As written, I read the request as a stacked bar chart for the one track with the highest monthly differential in AIRPLAY_STREAMS, where the stack is made up of the absolute number of streams and the percentage monthly differential. This did not make sense since monthly values for AIRPLAY_STREAMS are not given, as far as I could tell, and it is bad practice to mix scales in a bar chart, especially within a stacked column.

Instead, the plot above displays the "base" AIRPLAY_STREAMS count and the adjusted monthly growth as a count value for the top 5 tracks sorted by AIRPLAY_STREAMS_MONTHLY_DIFF_PER. The adjusted monthly growth is found by assuming the AIRPLAY_STREAMS_MONTHLY_DIFF_PER represents the growth in the last month as a percentage of AIRPLAY_STREAMS.

Interestingly, "Too Good at Raising Hell" has substantial growth given its relatively high existing stream count. The other 4 of the top 5 tracks have relatively low stream counts, which might be expected as their percentage growth is likely to be greater the lower the stream count is, i.e. an increase from 2 to 10 streams would not be very extreme or uncommon but constitutes a 400% growth.

  1. Calculate the total streams for each album. Albums have a unique identifier called UPC. After calculating the total streams, find the difference of total streams for each album from the average of each album.
  2. Calculate the average YOUTUBE_VIEWS for each album.

# Create a copy to avoid inadvertent changes to original dataset
da = Dataset.copy()

# Match the metric values to unique UPC and Track
da = da.groupby(["UPC", "TRACK_NAME"]).agg(
    {
    "ALBUM_NAME": "first",
    "YOUTUBE_VIEWS": "mean",
    "SOUNDCLOUD_PLAYS": "mean",

    "AIRPLAY_STREAMS": "mean",
    "SIRIUSXM_STREAMS": "mean"
    }
)

da["AverageYouTube"] = da["YOUTUBE_VIEWS"]
da["AverageStreams"] = da.sum(axis=1, numeric_only=True)
da["TotalStreams"] = da.sum(axis=1, numeric_only=True)

# Match the metric values to unique UPC
da = da.groupby(["UPC"]).agg(
    {
    "ALBUM_NAME": "first",
    "YOUTUBE_VIEWS": "sum",
    "SOUNDCLOUD_PLAYS": "sum",
    "SPOTIFY_PLAYS": "sum",
    "SHAZAM_COUNT": "sum",
    "TIKTOK_TOP_VIDEOS_VIEWS": "sum",
    "PANDORA_LIFETIME_STREAMS": "sum",
    "AIRPLAY_STREAMS": "sum",
    "SIRIUSXM_STREAMS": "sum",
    "AverageYouTube": "mean",
    "AverageStreams": "mean",
    "TotalStreams": "sum"
    }
)

# Calculate difference between total and average count of streams
da["Difference"] = da["TotalStreams"] - da["AverageStreams"]

Ranking Methodology:

  1. Aggregate tracks by Track Name, Artist Name, and ISRC with means to get "true" value of each recording.
  2. Aggregate tracks by Track Name and Artist Name with sums to get total value of each track.
  3. Aggregate records by Artist Name with sums to get total value of actual measures (YOUTUBE_VIEWS, etc) and with means to get average value of relative measures (SPOTIFY_POPULARITY, YOUTUBE_VIEWS_WEEKLY_DIFF_PER, etc).
  4. Calculate order statistics based on an overall and recent/short-term measure for each platform:
  • total Airplay plays
  • average Airplay plays monthly difference percentage
  • total Genius views
  • average Genius views monthly difference percentage
  • total Pandora views
  • average Pandora views monthly difference percentage
  • total Shazam plays
  • average Shazam plays monthly difference percentage
  • total SiriusXM plays
  • average SiriusXM plays monthly difference percentage
  • total Spotify plays
  • average Spotify plays monthly difference percentage
  • total Soundcloud views
  • average Soundcloud views monthly difference percentage
  • total TikTok views
  • average TikTok views monthly difference percentage
  • total YouTube views
  • average YouTube views monthly difference percentage
  1. Calculate weighted average of order statistics divided by number of artists ranked to create overall rank measure between 0 (popular) and 1 (not popular).

Then, test against mean CM_TRACK_RANK and SPOTIFY_POPULARITY as benchmarks to evaluate ranking system.

# Define weights
recency_weight = 1/2
weightAIRPLAY = 1/9
weightGENIUS = 1/9
weightPANDORA = 1/9
weightSHAZAM = 1/9
weightSIRIUSXM = 1/9
weightSPOTIFY = 1/9
weightSOUNDCLOUD = 1/9
weightTIKTOK = 1/9
weightYOUTUBE = 1/9
overall_weight = 1 - recency_weight

# Calculate weighted average rank
ranks["RANK"] = ranks["overallAIRPLAY"]*overall_weight*weightAIRPLAY + ranks["recentAIRPLAY"]*recency_weight*weightAIRPLAY + ranks["overallGENIUS"]*overall_weight*weightGENIUS + ranks["recentGENIUS"]*recency_weight*weightGENIUS + ranks["overallPANDORA"]*overall_weight*weightPANDORA + ranks["recentPANDORA"]*recency_weight*weightPANDORA + ranks["overallSHAZAM"]*overall_weight*weightSHAZAM + ranks["recentSHAZAM"]*recency_weight*weightSHAZAM + ranks["overallSIRIUSXM"]*overall_weight*weightSIRIUSXM + ranks["recentSIRIUSXM"]*recency_weight*weightSIRIUSXM + ranks["overallSPOTIFY"]*overall_weight*weightSPOTIFY + ranks["recentSPOTIFY"]*recency_weight*weightSPOTIFY + ranks["overallSOUNDCLOUD"]*overall_weight*weightSOUNDCLOUD + ranks["recentSOUNDCLOUD"]*recency_weight*weightSOUNDCLOUD + ranks["overallTIKTOK"]*overall_weight*weightTIKTOK + ranks["recentTIKTOK"]*recency_weight*weightTIKTOK + ranks["overallYOUTUBE"]*overall_weight*weightYOUTUBE + ranks["recentYOUTUBE"]*recency_weight*weightYOUTUBE

ranks["benchmarkCM"] = ranks["CM_TRACK_RANK"].rank(method="average",ascending=False,na_option='bottom',pct=True)
ranks["benchmarkSP"] = ranks["SPOTIFY_POPULARITY"].rank(method="average",ascending=False,na_option='bottom',pct=True)

# Compare created rank to benchmarks
ranks["compareRANK"] = ranks["RANK"].rank(method="average",ascending=False,na_option='bottom',pct=True)
ranks["diffCM"] = ranks["compareRANK"] - ranks["benchmarkCM"]
ranks["diffSP"] = ranks["compareRANK"] - ranks["benchmarkSP"]

print("The difference between RANK and CM_RANK has mean "+str(round(ranks["diffCM"].mean(), 3))+" and standard deviation "+str(round(ranks["diffCM"].std(), 3))+".")
print("The difference between RANK and SPOTIFY_POPULARITY has mean "+str(round(ranks["diffSP"].mean(), 3))+" and standard deviation "+str(round(ranks["diffSP"].std(), 3))+".")

# Sort and drop all but ARTIST_NAME and RANK
ranks = ranks.sort_values(by="RANK", ascending=False)
ranks = ranks[["ARTIST_NAME", "RANK"]]

# Groq (LLM) API Functions

def initialize_groq_client():
  """This function initializes and returns a Groq client with user data API key."""
  client = Groq(
      api_key=userdata.get("GROQ_API_KEY"),
  )
  return client

def get_artist_trivia(client, record):
    """This function generates and returns a piece of trivia using a groq call to Llama3, given a row with an ARTIST_NAME value."""
    chat_completion = client.chat.completions.create(
        messages=[
            {
                "role": "system",
                "content": "You are a well-read media journalist with a neutral tone. Answer concisely."
            },
            {
                "role": "user",
                "content": "What is a piece of niche trivia about "+record["ARTIST_NAME"],
            }
        ],
        model="llama3-8b-8192",
        temperature=0.75,
    )
    return chat_completion.choices[0].message.content

# Spotify API Functions

def spotify_authenticate():
  """This function handles Spotify API authentication and returns the access token received. NOTE: This token expires after 1 hour (3600 seconds)."""
  ### Fetch authentication credentials
  client_id = userdata.get("SPOTIFY_CLIENT_ID")
  client_secret = userdata.get("SPOTIFY_CLIENT_SECRET")
  ### Encode credentials
  client_creds = f"{client_id}:{client_secret}"
  client_creds_b64 = base64.b64encode(client_creds.encode())
  response = requests.post("https://accounts.spotify.com/api/token",
                         headers={"Authorization": "Basic "+client_creds_b64.decode(),
                                  "Content-Type": "application/x-www-form-urlencoded"},
                         data={"grant_type": "client_credentials"}
  )
  access_token = json.loads(response.content.decode().replace("'", '"'))["access_token"]
  return access_token

def get_artist_from_track_search(token, title):
  """Search for track with given title and returns artist of first search result."""
  search_url = "https://api.spotify.com/v1/search?q="+title.replace(" ", "%")+"&type=track"
  response = requests.get(search_url,
                          headers={
                              "Authorization": "Bearer "+token
                              }
                          )
  if response.status_code == 200:
    return json.loads(response.content.decode())["tracks"]["items"][0]["album"]["artists"][0]["name"]
  else:
    print("Failed to retrieve data")
    return

def get_artist_link(token, record):
  """Search for an artist with given name and returns link to Spotify page."""
  search_url = "https://api.spotify.com/v1/search?q="+record["ARTIST_NAME"].replace(" ", "%")+"&type=artist"
  response = requests.get(search_url,
                          headers={
                              "Authorization": "Bearer "+token
                              }
                          )
  if response.status_code == 200:
    return json.loads(response.content.decode())["artists"]["items"][0]["external_urls"]["spotify"]
  else:
    print(record["ARTIST_NAME"]+"Failed to retrieve data")
    return

# Artist-Level Info

# Get unique artist names
artists = pd.DataFrame({"ARTIST_NAME": tracks["ARTIST_NAME"].unique(), "TRIVIA": None, "LINK": None})

# Set up APIs
client = initialize_groq_client()
token = spotify_authenticate()

# Find fun facts and links for each artist
# NOTE: The use of a for loop here is chosen for simplicity and readability. If scaled up, this should be optimized instead for efficiency.
for i in range(artists.shape[0]):
  artists.loc[i, "TRIVIA"] = get_artist_trivia(client, artists.iloc[i])
  artists.loc[i, "LINK"] = get_artist_link(token, artists.iloc[i])

# Output artist data
artists.to_csv('/content/drive/MyDrive/Colab Notebooks/artists.csv',
               index=False)
